      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Locke argued that individuals possess inherent rights to life, liberty, and property, and free expression is a crucial component of liberty. For Locke, the social contract exists to protect these pre-existing rights, not to grant the government the power to dictate speech. Nozick would argue that such regulation constitutes a violation of self-ownership, as the state is coercing individuals into adhering to its preferred speech norms, which is an unjust seizure of autonomy.",
      "source": "target",
